sentences: Lloyd Lamar Green (born October 4, 1937) is an American steel guitarist noted for his extensive country music recording session career in Nashville performing on 116 No.1 country hits including Tammy Wynette’s
“D-I-V-O-R-C-E” (1968), Charlie Rich’s “Behind Closed Doors” (1973), The Oak Ridge Boys’ “Elvira” (1981), and Alan Jackson’s “Remember When” (2004).

In a career beginning in the mid 1960s and spanning a quarter-century, Green performed on more than 5000 recordings helping to create hits for scores of artists such as  Charley Pride, The Byrds, Johnny Cash, The Monkees, Don Williams, Paul McCartney, Bob Dylan, and many others.

Green was born on October 4, 1937 in Leaf, Mississippi, about 40 miles southeast of Hattiesburg.
Green said, "I became the poster child for the course when I was about 10 years old" (see photo).

About this time, lap steel guitars were getting pedals added to become the new pedal steel guitar and Green made an improvised pedal to add to his lap steel using an automobile accelerator pedal.: 211  He graduated from high school in 1955 and attended the University of Southern Mississippi.
In 1956 at age 19, he shocked his parents when he decided to take a year off college and move to Nashville to pursue music.

Green joined Faron Young's road band in December 1956 and stayed for 18 months.
Green joined Faron Young's road band in December 1956 and stayed for 18 months.
After a one month tour with Ferlin Husky, with money tight, he swore never to tour again: 183  and temporarily gave up music to work as a shoe salesman, not playing his guitar for two years.
After a one month tour with Ferlin Husky, with money tight, he swore never to tour again: 183  and temporarily gave up music to work as a shoe salesman, not playing his guitar for two years.
By the spring of 1963 he was ready to try music again.
By the spring of 1963 he was ready to try music again.
He said, "...the first week I was there, Slim Williamson, who owned Chart Records, hired me for a demo and master session."
In 1965, Green recorded a demo of a song called "The Bridge Washed Out" for Decca  recording artist Warner Mack.
It was a sharp-edged rapid style on muted strings now known as "chicken pickin'".
However, when the record came out three months later, it went straight to number one and ushered Green into the circle of studio hit-makers.
The unique style was copied by other steel players and remained in vogue for a few years thereafter.:
9 For the next 15 years, Green remained an elite studio player averaging 400 sessions a year including a string of 17 years of performing on at least three No. 1 songs each year.:

His 1968 performance on the Byrds' landmark album Sweetheart of the Rodeo, made the biggest impact on the overall American music audience: 13  and influenced generations of non-mainstream country guitarists.:

211  Music writer Peter Cooper called the album "a genre-bender that illuminated a path that led to modern California Country, Americana and alternative country music".: 11  On the album, Green was featured on You Ain't Goin' Nowhere, Hickory Wind, Nothing Was Delivered, and "One Hundred Years from Now".

211  Music writer Peter Cooper called the album "a genre-bender that illuminated a path that led to modern California Country, Americana and alternative country music".: 11  On the album, Green was featured on You Ain't Goin' Nowhere, Hickory Wind, Nothing Was Delivered, and "One Hundred Years from Now".

Green appeared with the Byrds an the Grand Ole Opry on March 16, 1968 to promote the album, but the Byrds were booed and heckled by the conservative Opry audience: 11  who considered them "long-haired outsiders".: 11 .
Part of the reason was that Gram Parsons assured the presenter that he would sing a couple of Merle Haggard tunes, but then instead inserted one his own songs, "Hickory Wind".
In 2018, Green and fellow steel guitarist JayDee Maness teamed up to make a tribute album called Journey to the Beginningː A Steel Guitar Tribute to the Byrds.
Many steel guitarists point to Green's 1968 performance on Charlie Pride's In Person album as the highlight of Green's career to that point.:
13 In addition to his work as a sideman, Green has cut several of his own LPs and had a top 40 hit with his instrumental version of “I Can See Clearly Now.”
Later years ==
In the 1980s, an inner ear ailment which distorted his hearing forced Green to stop working.:
13  Green said, "It was a nightmarish experience.
It went on for about a year before I quit doing sessions.

13  After a few years the problem resolved and he tried to return to session work after a 15 year hiatus but younger players and different styles had evolved and producers and record labels would not hire him.: 15  Green was inducted into the Steel Guitar Hall of Fame in 1988.

After hearing Bud Isaacs' playing on the hit song 'Slowly' in 1952, lap steel players began to switch to pedal steel.
In 1956, he was hired by Faron Young for an 18 month tour.
In 1956, he was hired by Faron Young for an 18 month tour.
Green left Faron Young in mid 1958, and received a new guitar courtesy of Shot Jackson, who traded Green's old Fender for a Rickenbacker doubleneck with two retrofitted pedals.
Green used this "Rick" for the next three years.
In 1963, he played a double-neck Bigsby on which Jackson added six pedals.
By 1964 he played Sho-Bud steels and in 1966 changed to a Sho-Bud "fingertip" double 10 model which he played on many country hits.

In 1973, Green designed a guitar for Sho-Bud.
